Performance efficiency.

Performance efficiency is the pillar about hitting your performance targets without overspending. Pick the right compute: functions for sporadic event work, serverless containers for steady ones, instances for sustained or custom workloads, and arm-based processors for better price-performance on most workloads. Pick the right data engine per access pattern: relational for transactions, the key-value store for any-scale lookups, the warehouse for analytics, object storage with a query service for an ad-hoc lake, the search service for search, and a cache for hot data.

Cache aggressively at every layer, at the edge, near the application, and in front of the key-value store when latency demands. Use asynchronous patterns, queues, topics, the event bus, and workflows, to decouple latency-sensitive paths from slow downstream work. Set auto-scaling rules with cooldowns so nothing flaps, aggressive on scale-out and conservative on scale-in. Optimize the network with placement groups, enhanced networking, and the global accelerator. And match storage class to access.

The lever that pays everyone back is reviewing the architecture every quarter for newer instance generations and managed-service replacements that didn't exist when you designed it.
